==English==

===Etymology===
[[Old English]] ''twein''.

===Number===
'''twain'''
# {{dated}} The number [[two]], nearly obsolete in common discourse, but used in [[poetry]] and [[burlesque]].

===Quotes===
* ''And whosoever shall compel thee to go a mile, go with him '''twain'''''. [[Matthew]] 5:41.
* ''Til that the deeth departe shal us '''tweyne''''' ... Chaucer, Knight's Tale, ln. 1632.  
* ''And never the twain shall meet'' ... Kipling

